<Layout>
	<main>
		<h1> All about Cats: </h1>
		<LeaveButton/>
		<div class = "blog-container">
			<h2> Why Cats Continue to Captivate Us </h2>
			<img src = "../../images/cat1.jpeg">
			<p> 
				Cats have lived alongside humans for thousands of years, yet they remain some of 
				the most mysterious and captivating animals in our lives. Their mix of independence, 
				affection, curiosity, and elegance makes them uniquely appealing to people across cultures 
				and time periods. 
			</p>
			<h2> A History of Companionship </h2>
			<p> 
				Domestication of cats began roughly 10,000 years ago, when early humans stored grain that attracted 
				rodents. Wildcats naturally followed the food source, and humans quickly realized that these agile hunters 
				were valuable allies. Over time, the partnership evolved: people provided shelter and safety, and cats offered 
				pest control and companionship.
			</p>
			<h2>The Perfect Balance of Independence and Affection</h2>
			<img src = "../../images/cat2.jpeg">
			<p>
				One of the reasons cats are so beloved is their balance between self-sufficiency and emotional connection. Unlike dogs, 
				cats generally don’t rely on constant attention. They are comfortable entertaining themselves, grooming, and exploring. 
				Yet, when a cat chooses to curl up on your lap or follow you around the house, it feels like a genuine show of trust. <br><br>

				Their affectionate behaviors—slow blinking, head bumping, gentle purring—are subtle but deeply meaningful signals of comfort and attachment.
			</p>
			<h2>Health and Well-Being</h2>
			<p>
				Cats are relatively low-maintenance pets, but they still require attentive care. Regular veterinary visits, proper nutrition, enrichment, and play 
				are essential. Mental stimulation is especially important—interactive toys, climbing structures, and window perches can all help keep a cat healthy and engaged. <br><br>

				Indoor cats generally live longer and safer lives than outdoor cats, though outdoor access through secure enclosures or harness training can give them the best of both worlds.
			</p>
			
		<div>
	</main>
</Layout>

